VALUES
(43, 19, 26, 43, 21, 20, 20, 'whom he loved', 'Connection of the Beloved Disciple', 'Both passages emphasize the presence of ''the disciple whom Jesus loved.'' In John 19:26, this disciple is present at the crucifixion, while in John 21:20, he is noted as following Jesus, highlighting his significance in the narrative.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 27, 40, 12, 48, 50, 'Behold thy mother!', 'Family in Christ', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of familial relationships in a spiritual context. In John, Jesus entrusts his mother to a disciple, while in Matthew, he redefines family as those who do the will of God.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 27, 43, 16, 32, 32, 'Behold thy mother!', 'Connection of Solitude and Care', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of being alone and the importance of relationships. In John 19:27, the disciple takes Mary into his home, highlighting care amidst solitude, while John 16:32 speaks of scattering and leaving Jesus alone, yet He acknowledges the Father''s presence.', 'theme', 0.356, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 27, 54, 5, 2, 4, 'Behold thy mother!', 'Connection of Care for Family', 'This connection highlights the importance of familial responsibility and care. In John 19:27, the disciple takes Mary into his home, reflecting the duty to care for one''s mother, which is echoed in 1 Timothy 5:2-4, where honoring and providing for widows and parents is emphasized.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 27, 62, 3, 18, 19, NULL, 'Love in Action', 'This connection highlights the theme of love expressed through actions. In John 19:27, the disciple takes Mary into his home, demonstrating love in deed, while 1 John 3:18 emphasizes loving not just in word but in deed and truth.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 27, 43, 1, 11, 11, 'Behold thy mother!', 'Connection of Belonging and Rejection', 'This connection highlights the theme of belonging, as Jesus entrusts his mother to the disciple, indicating a personal relationship. In contrast, the target passage notes that Jesus came to his own but was not received, emphasizing a sense of rejection from those he came to. Both passages reflect the complexities of familial and communal acceptance.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 27, 1, 45, 8, 8, 'Behold thy mother!', 'Family and Responsibility', 'This connection highlights themes of familial duty and care. In John 19:27, the disciple takes Mary into his home, reflecting a protective role, similar to Joseph''s assertion of responsibility in Genesis 45:8 as he becomes a father figure to Pharaoh.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 27, 1, 47, 12, 12, NULL, 'Nourishment and Care', 'This connection highlights the theme of care and provision in both passages. In John 19:27, the disciple takes Mary into his home, providing for her, while in Genesis 47:12, Joseph nourishes his family, ensuring their well-being.', 'theme', 0.3, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 28, 19, 69, 21, 21, 'I thirst', 'Connection of Thirst and Vinegar', 'This connection highlights the theme of thirst in both passages. Jesus'' declaration ''I thirst'' in John 19:28 parallels the mention of being given vinegar to drink in Psalms 69:21.', 'theme', 1.0, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 28, 19, 22, 15, 15, 'I thirst', 'Connection of Thirst and Suffering', 'This connection highlights the theme of physical suffering and thirst in both passages. Jesus'' declaration of ''I thirst'' in John resonates with the imagery of dryness and distress found in Psalms, specifically the phrase ''my strength is dried up.''', 'theme', 0.72, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 28, 43, 19, 30, 30, 'that the scripture might be fulfilled', 'Connection of Fulfillment and Completion', 'This connection highlights the progression from Jesus'' acknowledgment of thirst to the declaration of completion. Both passages emphasize the fulfillment of scripture and the culmination of Jesus'' mission.', 'theme', 0.552, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 28, 42, 22, 37, 37, 'that the scripture might be fulfilled', 'Fulfillment of Scripture', 'This connection highlights the theme of fulfillment in both passages. In John 19:28, Jesus expresses a physical need to fulfill scripture, while in Luke 22:37, he acknowledges that what is written about him must be accomplished.', 'theme', 0.44699999999999995, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 28, 42, 18, 31, 31, NULL, 'Fulfillment of Scripture', 'Both passages emphasize the completion of prophetic scripture. In John, Jesus acknowledges that all things are accomplished, while in Luke, he states that all things written by the prophets shall be accomplished.', 'theme', 0.419, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 28, 43, 19, 24, 24, 'that the scripture might be fulfilled', 'Fulfillment of Scripture', 'Both passages emphasize the fulfillment of scripture in the events surrounding Jesus'' crucifixion. In John 19:24, the soldiers'' actions fulfill a prophecy about dividing garments, while in John 19:28, Jesus'' statement ''I thirst'' also fulfills scripture.', 'prophecy', 0.412, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 28, 44, 13, 29, 29, 'that the scripture might be fulfilled', 'Fulfillment of Scripture', 'This connection highlights the theme of fulfilling scripture in both passages. John 19:28 emphasizes Jesus'' awareness of fulfilling all things, while Acts 13:29 states they fulfilled all that was written of him.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 29, 4, 19, 18, 18, 'hyssop', 'Hyssop as a Symbol of Purity', 'Both passages emphasize the use of hyssop in purification rituals. In Numbers, hyssop is used to sprinkle water for cleansing, while in John, it is used to offer vinegar to Jesus, linking the themes of cleansing and sacrifice.', 'theme', 0.40499999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 29, 42, 23, 36, 36, NULL, 'Vinegar Offered to Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize the offering of vinegar to Jesus during his crucifixion. This connection highlights the mocking nature of the soldiers in both accounts.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 29, 41, 15, 36, 36, 'filled a spunge with vinegar', 'Connection of Vinegar References', 'Both passages emphasize the use of vinegar given to Jesus during his crucifixion. The act of offering vinegar is a shared detail that highlights the moment of suffering in both accounts.', 'parallel', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 29, 40, 27, 48, 48, 'filled a spunge with vinegar', 'Connection of Vinegar References', 'Both passages emphasize the act of offering vinegar to Jesus while he was on the cross. The use of a sponge in both accounts highlights a shared detail in the narrative of his crucifixion.', 'parallel', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 29, 2, 12, 22, 22, 'hyssop', 'Hyssop in Crucifixion and Passover', 'Both passages emphasize the use of hyssop in significant rituals. In John, hyssop is used to offer vinegar to Jesus, while in Exodus, it is used to apply blood during Passover, highlighting its symbolic role in salvation.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 29, 19, 51, 7, 7, 'hyssop', 'Hyssop as a Symbol of Purity', 'This connection highlights the use of hyssop in both passages, where it serves as a means of cleansing. In John 19:29, hyssop is used to offer vinegar to Jesus, while in Psalms 51:7, it symbolizes purification and washing away sin.', 'keyword', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 29, 40, 27, 34, 34, 'vinegar', 'Connection of Vinegar References', 'Both passages emphasize the presence of vinegar offered to Jesus during his crucifixion. John specifies the use of a sponge and hyssop, while Matthew mentions vinegar mingled with gall, highlighting a shared theme of sour drink.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 30, 43, 17, 4, 4, 'It is finished', 'Completion of Jesus'' Mission', 'Both passages emphasize the completion of Jesus'' work. In John 17:4, Jesus states, ''I have finished the work,'' which connects to His declaration in John 19:30, ''It is finished.'' This connection highlights the fulfillment of His mission on earth.', 'theme', 0.9649999999999999, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 30, 50, 2, 8, 8, NULL, 'Connection of Obedience and Death', 'This connection highlights Jesus'' obedience unto death in Philippians, paralleling his declaration of completion in John. Both passages emphasize the significance of Jesus'' death on the cross.', 'theme', 0.685, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 30, 51, 2, 14, 17, 'It is finished', 'Completion of the Law', 'This connection highlights the completion of Jesus'' mission in John 19:30, where he declares, ''It is finished,'' paralleling Colossians 2:14''s theme of the law being blotted out. Both passages emphasize the triumph over ordinances and spiritual powers through Christ''s sacrifice.', 'theme', 0.629, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 30, 58, 12, 2, 2, 'It is finished', 'Completion of Jesus'' Mission', 'This connection highlights the theme of Jesus'' role in completing faith. In John 19:30, Jesus declares, ''It is finished,'' indicating the fulfillment of His mission, while Hebrews 12:2 refers to Him as the ''finisher of our faith,'' emphasizing His pivotal role in salvation.', 'theme', 0.538, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 30, 43, 10, 11, 11, 'It is finished', 'Connection of Sacrificial Themes', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of sacrifice. In John 10:11, Jesus identifies as the good shepherd who gives his life, while in John 19:30, he declares, ''It is finished,'' signifying the completion of his sacrificial mission.', 'theme', 0.5309999999999999, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 30, 27, 9, 24, 24, 'It is finished', 'Completion of Divine Purpose', 'This connection highlights the theme of completion in both passages. John 19:30''s ''It is finished'' resonates with Daniel 9:24''s purpose to ''finish the transgression'' and ''make an end of sins.''', 'theme', 0.517, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 30, 23, 53, 10, 10, 'It is finished', 'Connection of Sacrifice and Completion', 'This connection highlights the theme of Jesus'' sacrificial role. In John 19:30, ''It is finished'' signifies the completion of his offering, while Isaiah 53:10 speaks of making his soul an offering for sin.', 'theme', 0.503, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 31, 43, 19, 14, 14, 'the preparation', 'Preparation and Passover Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of preparation in both passages. John 19:31 refers to the preparation for the Sabbath, while John 19:14 mentions the preparation of the Passover, linking the significance of these events.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini')
